        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to use a single pointing to map the central region of NGC0524, which has a relaxed molecular disk but suppressed star formation, in the CO(2-1) line (Band 6). The molecular disk is smaller than the field of view of the telescope at this frequency. Using the extended array configuration C34-6 results in a synthesised beam of ~0.25”, which will yield high-resolution CO measurements that can be combined with our recent analysis of star formation and star clusters in this region, using 0.05” resolution UV/optical imaging from the HST. 

The largest angular scale visible in this array configuration is ~4.0”, much larger than the angular scales over which ultraviolet (UV) structures that trace the star formation and therefore the gas are visible. In addition, individual GMCs have typical sizes of 15 - 90 pc at CO(1-0) (Bolatto et al. 2008), or 0.22 -  1.38” at our adopted distance of 23 Mpc (Tonry et al. ApJ, 546, 681). We therefore do not expect to resolve out much flux within the region imaged. To check this, we simulated a mock ALMA data cube using the CASA simulator, using as input an dust map of the central region (see Fig 2, right panel). These simulations confirmed that very little flux will be lost.
Several key science aims in our proposal will leverage this complementary HST data at 0.05” resolution (which will be rebinned to the resolution of the ALMA images for the analysis). 
 

Correlator setup:

We request a frequency set-up allowing us to cover the CO(2-1) line with a 1875 MHz baseband (~2458 km/s) and a raw spectral resolution of 0.976 MHz (~1.3 km/s). This covers the entire velocity width expected. We include other bands over additional molecular species that would give us complimentary information and are accessible simultaneously, but these do not drive our time request. 

 

Requested sensitivity:

Here we aim to be able to detect individual molecular clouds, which have typical surface densities of ~85 Msun/pc^2. In order to detect such a cloud with a S/N of 5 we require a rms flux of ~0.78 mJy/beam in 2.5 km/s channels. The ALMA Observing Tool suggests that reaching this limit at 230 GHz with the default 1.26 mm PWV and the C34-6 array configuration will require ~1.87 hr on-source, or ~3.87 hours including all calibrations and overheads.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
