    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to obtain a high resolution map of CO(2-1) in NGC0524, an elliptical galaxy which is forming stars significantly less efficiently (by a factor of ~2) than expected from normal star-formation relations. These observations will allow us to determine, 1) the stability of the gas against self-gravity, shear and tidal forces in a spatially-resolved manner 2) to determine the cloud mass and surface density functions 3) to detect streaming/non-circular motions in the gas and 4) to estimate the CO-to-H2 (X_CO) conversion factor directly. From these physical quantities, we will determine what physical processes are causing the suppression of star formation, shedding light on the ongoing evolution of bulge dominated galaxies and the underlying physics of the star-formation process itself.
</prp:abstract>
